title: Appointments to Elderly Commission
content_text:
p>    The Government today (July 28) announced the appointment of Dr Leong 
    Che-hung as Chairman of the Elderly Commission and Professor Alfred Chan 
    Cheung-ming, as Vice-Chairman.    Six new members were also appointed, and three incumbent members 
    re-appointed. The appointments/re-appointments will take effect from 
    Saturday (July 30) for a term of two years.  Dr Leong is a private medical practitioner specialising in urology. 
    He has extensive experience in public service and is currently the

He has extensive experience in public service and is currently the 
    Chairperson of the Council on Human Reproductive Technology. He was the 
    Chairman of the Hospital Authority from October 2002 to September 2004 and 
    served as a Legislative Councillor from 1988 to 2000.    Speaking on the new appointments, the Secretary for Health, Welfare 
    and Food, Dr York Chow, expressed gratitude to Dr Leong for taking up this 
    important position when population ageing posed many challenges to Hong

important position when population ageing posed many challenges to Hong 
    Kong.  "Dr Leong's wealth of experience in health and welfare matters made 
    him eminently suitable for the appointment to lead the commission in 
    providing advice to the Government on elderly policies," he added.  Prof Chan is a professor in Sociology and Gerontology at the Lingnan 
    University and an academic in ageing research and studies. He is Director of 
    the Asia-Pacific Institute of Ageing Studies (APIAS) and Consultant for the

the Asia-Pacific Institute of Ageing Studies (APIAS) and Consultant for the 
    Expert Group on Ageing Policy, United Nation Economics and Social Commission 
    for Asia and the Pacific (UNESCAP).  Dr Chow was confident that Prof Chan, with his expertise in sociology 
    and gerontology, would provide valuable input to the future work of the 
    Elderly Commission.  The six new members are Mr Kenneth Chan Chi-yuk, Mr Chan Han-pan,

Prof Helen Chiu Fung-kum, Rev Dorothy Lau Wai-ling, Mr Leo Ma Chan-hang, and Dr Loretta Yam Yin-chun. Brief biographies of the members are given in the Annex. The three incumbent members who have been re-appointed are Dr Susie

Lum Shun-sui, Mr Star Chan Iu-seng and Dr Lam Ching-choi.  Dr Chow looked forward to the contribution of members who came from 
    various social backgrounds and areas of expertise in the development of 
    elderly services in Hong Kong.  Meanwhile, Dr Chow thanked the outgoing members �V the Hon Tam 
    Yiu-chung, Prof Iris Chi, Mrs Peggy Lam Pei Yu-dja, Dr Raymond Wu Wai-yung, 
    Mr Michael Lai Kam-cheung and Mr Peter Wong Hong-yuen �V for their valuable

contributions during their tenure. He particularly commended the Hon Tam 
    Yiu-chung for his strong leadership and sterling work in steering the 
    commission since its inception in 1997.  The new membership list of the Elderly Commission with effect from

July 30, 2005 is as follows:  Chairman:  Dr Leong Che-hung, GBS, JP  Vice-Chairman:  Prof Alfred Chan Cheung-ming, JP  Non-official Members:  Dr Ng Yau-yung, JP  Dr Susie Lum Shun-sui  Ms Anita Wong Yiu-ming  Mr Star Chan Iu-seng, BBS  Dr Lam Ching-choi, JP  Prof Jean Woo  Mr Kenneth Chan Chi-yuk  Mr Chan Han-pan  Prof Helen Chiu Fung-kum  Rev Dorothy

Mr Chan Han-pan  Prof Helen Chiu Fung-kum  Rev Dorothy Lau Wai-ling, JP  Mr Leo Ma Chan-hang  Dr Loretta Yam Yin-chun, BBS  Official members:  Secretary for Education and Manpower or representative  Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food or representative  Secretary for Housing, Planning and Lands or representative  Director of Health or representative  Director of Housing or representative  Director of Social Welfare or representative  Chief Executive, Hospital Authority or representative
